sible by construction: anything the web app can show or do, your client can too, over HTTP or MCP."],[287,"The web app: a usage chip on run cards, spent-vs-limit budget pairing on run detail, and fleet-wide totals in `GET /api/dashboard` (`stats.usage`)."],[1415,"The web app's workflow create/edit screens are ordinary clients of `POST /api/workflows` and `PATCH /api/workflows/{id}`: they submit the definition with inline source bytes and the Hub publishes the bundle, exactly as above. There is no separate, privileged authoring path."],[1379,"The web editor"],[1347,"The workflow concluded a human must act."],[218,"The workflow must opt in via `workflow.hooks.allowedProfiles` (a list of profile slugs, or `\"*\"`); no opt-in means no hooks, default-closed."],[1404,"The workflow source bytes, sent inline as a string (aliases: `workflow.sourceBytes`, `workflow.code`)."],[497,"the workflow's declared `workflow.secrets` list, and"],[176,"The workflow's runs."],[1164,"Then let the CLI write your AI client's MCP config:"],[1110,"Then set `BASE_URL=https://hub.example.com` in the Hub's env file and restart.\nAn `https://` base URL switches the Hub into production session mode. If the\nproxy is not on loopback, set the trust-proxy configuration accordingly so\nclient IPs (used by rate limiting) are read from `X-Forwarded-For` only when\nthat header is trustworthy."],[1055,"Then start the runner against the current remote (it inherits the remote's URL\nand token, or `RUNYARD_HUB_URL` / `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN`):"],[20,"This page takes you from a fresh Linux box to a completed workflow run with logs and artifacts in the Hub."],[403,"Three ways to use it:"],[596,"Tickets on the Work board — the durable unit of company work that workflows and runs execute for."],[947,"Timed approvals and fallback"],[92,"Timed approvals with fallback"],[1166,"To configure a client by hand, print the snippet instead:"],[30,"To run an ad-hoc runner on any other machine (for example your laptop, for `local` execution):"],[766,"token"],[769,"token"],[570,"Token name and scopes."],[1193,"Tokens"],[516,"Tokens & Scopes"],[798,"Tokens are minted by an admin (web UI, `POST /api/tokens`, or the CLI) and carry\n**scopes**:"],[1284,"Tokens carry scopes; admins mint them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`."],[1021,"Tokens, audit, and catalog"],[1174,"Tools"],[1211,"Tools marked † require an admin-scoped token."],[1228,"Trigger"],[213,"Trigger a preview deploy for a configured project."],[1309,"Troubleshooting"],[1259,"Trust boundary"],[1258,"Trust boundary, token scopes, secrets handling, runner sandboxing, and production posture for a Runyard deployment."],[1054,"Turn a machine into a runner in three steps. First scaffold a workspace\n(requires `bun` and the `smithers` engine on `PATH`; it warns if no `claude`,\n`codex`, or `pi` agent CLI is found):"],[1283,"Two narrow exceptions authenticate by other means: `POST /api/telegram/webhook` is verified against the configured bot and webhook secret, and `POST /api/workflow-endpoints/{slug}` submissions authenticate with that endpoint's own secret (below). `GET /api/setup` returns only a reduced identity payload (instance name, auth mode) to unauthenticated callers."],[1350,"Unclassified failure."],[863,"Unified ascending timeline (`since=<iso>`, `limit=<n>`); backs `runyard tail`"],[1368,"Unified timeline: status transitions, events, artifacts as NDJSON."],[1024,"Updating a host install"],[1377,"Updating a workflow"],[698,"Updating a workflow bumps its integer `version` and snapshots the previous definition. `GET /api/workflows/{name}/versions` lists the versions observed on past runs, and every run records the `workflowVersion` it executed. Bundle versions count separately, per publish."],[360,"Usage and budgets"],[299,"Usage is captured at the **inference boundary**, through two paths:"],[268,"Usage metering & budgets"],[270,"Usage records and the run aggregate"],[545,"Use for"],[114,"Values"],[997,"Variable"],[1112,"Variable"],[1133,"Variable"],[22,"Verify the Hub is up:"],[1361,"Verify, in order: `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` and `TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_CHAT_ID` are set on the Hub; the bot's webhook points at `https://hub.example.com/api/telegram/webhook` with the matching `TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_SECRET`; the bot is a member of the target chat; and the users pressing buttons are listed in `TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_USER_IDS`. Response-endpoint deliveries record their state (`status`, `attempts`, `last_error`) on `GET /api/runs/{id}` under `responseEndpoints[]`."],[673,"Versioning"],[1219,"Versioning and releases"],[724,"Versions seen on runs."],[156,"View"],[172,"Visual graph tab."],[1336,"Wait and re-run; check the provider account."],[1018,"Watch and manage runs"],[956,"Web app"],[33,"Web: open **Workflows**, pick &#x2A;*Hello (Smithers proof)**, fill in `topic`, and click Run."],[950,"Webhook"],[448,"What a fire produces"],[968,"What each decision does depends on the card's kind:"],[1,"What is Runyard"],[1229,"What it does"],[758,"What it gives you"],[48,"What it is"],[97,"What it represents"],[1364,"What it tells you"],[1266,"What stays out of public discovery docs"],[1390,"What the workflow does; shown in the catalog and menus."],[1327,"What to do"],[195,"When an agent hands off to a human — \"approve this\", \"read the logs\" — prefer relaying the payload's deep link over describing where to click."],[387,"When execution is interrupted by a condition a human can fix — the classic case is **the provider account ran out of credits** — the run parks as `paused` instead of failing. Pause metadata lives on `run.pause`:"],[1088,"When it finishes it prints next steps: sign in with the bootstrap token, mint a\nrunner-scoped token, put it in `/etc/runyard/runner.env`, and restart the runner\nunit."],[945,"Where approvals appear"],[1071,"Where state lives"],[19,"Where to go next"],[1319,"Where to look, generally"],[279,"Where usage appears:"],[690,"Whether new runs hold for an approval before executing."],[140